   352	### `reference/compose/healthcheck/smoke.sh`
   353	
   354	Bash script, exits 0 on success. Used by the new CI job and runnable
   355	locally for verification. Behavior:
   356	
   357	```bash
   358	#!/usr/bin/env bash
   359	set -euo pipefail
   360	
   361	# Tooling preflight — fail fast with a clear message if a required
   362	# binary is missing. `docker compose` is also expected; the CI job
   363	# preflights it separately, but local users get the diagnostic here.
   364	for tool in docker jq; do
   365	    command -v "$tool" >/dev/null || {
   366	        echo "smoke.sh requires '$tool' on PATH" >&2
   367	        exit 2
   368	    }
   369	done
   370	
   371	# Bring the stack up using .env.example as the source of truth.
   372	# (Copy to a temp .env if invoked from CI to avoid mutating the
   373	# checked-in file.)
   374	TMPENV="$(mktemp)"
   375	trap 'rm -f "$TMPENV"; docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" down -v' EXIT
   376	cp .env.example "$TMPENV"
   377	
   378	docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" up -d --wait --wait-timeout 120
   379	
   380	# Assert both long-running services are healthy.
   381	# `--wait` already enforces this, but we re-check for clarity in CI logs.
   382	docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" ps
   383	
   384	# Assert all three named volumes were created at compose-up time.
   385	# blob-init mounts eden-blob-data so Compose creates it; postgres and
   386	# gitea mount their own data volumes the usual way. Project-prefixed
   387	# volume names follow the "<project>_<volume>" convention; the project
   388	# name is fixed by `name: eden-reference` in compose.yaml and is also
   389	# echoed below for traceability.
   390	PROJECT="$(docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" \
   391	            config --format json | jq -r '.name')"
   392	test "$PROJECT" = "eden-reference" \
   393	    || { echo "unexpected project name: $PROJECT"; exit 1; }
   394	for vol in eden-postgres-data eden-gitea-data eden-blob-data; do
   395	    docker volume inspect "${PROJECT}_${vol}" >/dev/null
   396	done
   397	
   398	# Confirm blob-init actually exited 0 (--wait would have failed
   399	# otherwise, but re-checking gives a useful CI log line). Using
   400	# `docker inspect` against the explicit container_name avoids
   401	# `docker compose ps --format json` shape variations across Compose
   402	# versions (some emit NDJSON, some emit a JSON array).
   403	test "$(docker inspect --format '{{.State.ExitCode}}' eden-blob-init)" = "0"
   404	
   405	# Assert Postgres is accepting connections (independent of healthcheck).
   406	docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" exec -T postgres \
   407	    pg_isready -U eden -d eden
   408	
   409	# Assert Gitea API responds.
   410	GITEA_PORT="$(grep ^GITEA_HOST_PORT "$TMPENV" | cut -d= -f2)"
   411	curl -fsS "http://localhost:${GITEA_PORT}/api/v1/version" | grep -q '"version":'
   412	
   413	echo "PASS"
   414	```
   415	
   416	Notes:
   417	
   418	- The `trap` ensures teardown runs even on assertion failure, so
   419	  CI runs don't leave dangling volumes.
   420	- `--wait --wait-timeout 120` (Compose v2 feature) makes `up`
   421	  block until every long-running service is healthy and every
   422	  one-shot has exited 0, or 2min elapses, exiting non-zero if any
   423	  service fails. This is the cleanest way to encode "everything
   424	  came up cleanly" in a script. Verified during planning that
   425	  one-shot services are handled correctly by `--wait`.
   426	- The volume name is the standard `<project>_<volume>` Compose
   427	  convention. The script reads the project name from
   428	  `docker compose config` and asserts it equals
   429	  `eden-reference` (matching the `name:` field in `compose.yaml`)
   430	  before applying the prefix, so a future rename of `name:`
   431	  fails the smoke test loudly rather than silently checking
   432	  the wrong volumes.
