   457	Reasoning: the existing required checks (`docs-lint`,
   458	`schema-validity`, `python-lint`, `python-typecheck`, `python-test`,
   459	`schema-parity`) are sufficient to gate a 10a merge; adding
   460	`compose-smoke` to protection on the *same* PR that introduces it

 succeeded in 0ms:
    80	    flavors and explicitly recommends rootless for new deployments).
    81	- **Default ports are off the well-known channels** (Postgres on 5433,
    82	  Gitea on 3001) so a developer's existing local Postgres / Gitea
    83	  doesn't collide. Documented in `.env.example`. Real production
    84	  deployments override.
    85	- **Secrets via `.env` only.** No secrets baked into the Compose file.
    86	  `.env.example` ships canned dev defaults; the real `.env` is
    87	  gitignored. CI uses `.env.example` as-is — these are throwaway
    88	  values, not real credentials.
    89	- **Healthchecks on every long-running infra service.** Compose
    90	  `depends_on` semantics with `condition: service_healthy` are the
    91	  only safe way to chain bring-up; without healthchecks, "up" means
    92	  "container process started," not "Postgres is accepting
    93	  connections." `postgres` and `gitea` define a `healthcheck:`
    94	  block; `blob-init` is a one-shot whose contract is "exit 0" (no
    95	  long-running process to health-check). Downstream services in
    96	  10b/10d gate on `service_healthy` for postgres/gitea and on
    97	  `service_completed_successfully` for blob-init.
    98	- **Volume strategy — named volumes, not bind mounts.** Named volumes
    99	  (`eden-postgres-data`, `eden-gitea-data`, `eden-blob-data`) are
   100	  Compose-managed, survive `compose down` (use `compose down -v` to
   101	  wipe), and don't pollute the repo with `_data/` directories. Bind
   102	  mounts work but tie data location to the developer's filesystem
   103	  layout, which gets fragile when CI lays things out differently.
   104	- **Postgres bootstrap via `/docker-entrypoint-initdb.d/`.** The
   105	  official Postgres image runs every `*.sql` and `*.sh` in that
   106	  directory the *first* time the data volume is empty. We ship one
   107	  init SQL file: `01-create-eden-db.sql`, which creates the `eden`
   108	  database and the `eden` role with an env-var-driven password.
   109	  (`POSTGRES_DB=eden` + `POSTGRES_USER=eden` + `POSTGRES_PASSWORD=…`
   110	  in `.env` is the simpler path and we use that — the init SQL is
   111	  needed only if we want extensions or extra roles. **Decision:**
   112	  use env-var bootstrap, **no init SQL file** in 10a. If a later
   113	  chunk needs `pg_stat_statements` or a second role we add init SQL
   114	  then. Keeps 10a smaller.)
   115	- **Gitea bootstrap via env vars.** Gitea respects `GITEA__<section>__<key>`
   116	  env vars at startup. We set the minimum needed for headless
   117	  operation: install lock skipped, no telemetry, JWT secret pinned
   118	  via `.env`, admin user *not* auto-created in 10a — 10c's
   119	  `setup-experiment` script will create the admin via the API or
   120	  `gitea admin user create` once there's a real consumer. (Creating
   121	  an admin in 10a means we'd have to choose a token-issuing scheme
   122	  before we have anything to issue tokens for.)
   123	- **Blob volume = named volume + one-shot `blob-init` mounter.**
   124	  Empirical Compose behavior verified during planning: a
   125	  top-level `volumes:` declaration **does not** cause Compose to
   126	  create the volume unless at least one service mounts it. A
   127	  bare declaration (no mount, no init service) leaves
   128	  `docker volume ls` empty after `compose up`. To make 10a's
   129	  deliverable real, we ship a one-shot `blob-init` busybox
   130	  container that mounts `eden-blob-data` at `/var/lib/eden/blobs`,
   131	  runs `mkdir -p`, and exits 0. `restart: "no"` prevents the
   132	  exited container from looping; `docker compose up --wait`
   133	  semantics for one-shot services were also verified during
   134	  planning — `--wait` returns exit 0 when a one-shot container
   135	  exits 0, so the smoke test gets a clean signal. Downstream
   136	  services in 10b/10d mount the same volume.
   137	- **10a's blob-volume guarantee is "volume exists," not
   138	  "writable by the eventual 10d producer."** `blob-init` runs as
   139	  BusyBox root, and any in-container writability check 10a runs
   140	  is also from a root container — that proves "root can write,"
   141	  which is uninformative for the eventual non-root LLM-worker
   142	  containers in 10d. We deliberately do **not** make a
   143	  uid/gid/perm contract in 10a. 10d picks the user model when
   144	  the first real producer lands and is responsible for any
   145	  ownership/`chmod`/`chown` step it needs. 10a's smoke test
   146	  asserts existence (`docker volume inspect`) and that the
   147	  `blob-init` container exited 0 — nothing more about the volume.
   148	- **Compose file format = `compose.yaml` (no `version:` field).**
   149	  Modern Docker Compose deprecated the top-level `version:` key and
   150	  Docker recommends using just `compose.yaml`. We name the file
   151	  `compose.yaml` (not `docker-compose.yml`) and omit `version:`.
   152	  `docker compose` (v2 plugin, the only supported flavor) accepts
   153	  both filenames; users on extremely old `docker-compose` (v1, EOL)
   154	  may be surprised, and that's an acceptable cost — v1 has been
   155	  unmaintained for 18+ months.
